  "prompt": "What are some cultural faux pas in Hungary?",
  "response": "When visiting Hungary, it's important to be aware of certain cultural customs and etiquette to avoid unintentional faux pas. Here are some to keep in mind:\n\n1. **Greetings**: A firm handshake is the standard greeting. Avoid using first names unless invited to do so. When greeting a group, do so individually.\n\n2. **Punctuality**: Being late is considered disrespectful. Always strive to be on time for meetings, dinners, and social gatherings.\n\n3. **Dining Etiquette**: Keep your hands on the table (but not your elbows) while eating. It\u2019s common to wait for the host to start the meal or toast before beginning to eat.\n\n4. **Toasting**: When toasting, maintain eye contact and do so with a smile. It's customary to use the phrase \"Eg\u00e9szs\u00e9gedre!\" (To your health!).\n\n5. **Gift Giving**: If invited to someone\u2019s home, bringing a small gift (like wine or flowers) is appreciated. Avoid giving an even number of flowers; odd numbers are preferred.\n\n6. **Personal Space**: While Hungarians may appear reserved initially, they appreciate friendly and warm interactions once a relationship is established. Respect personal space unless they seem comfortable with closer proximity.\n\n7. **Tipping**: Tipping is common in restaurants, usually around 10-15%. It\u2019s appreciated to round up the bill or leave small change.\n\n8. **Language**: While many Hungarians speak English, especially in urban areas, it\u2019s respectful to learn a few basic Hungarian phrases. A simple \"k\u00f6sz\u00f6n\u00f6m\" (thank you) can go a long way.\n\n9. **Political Sensitivities**: Be cautious when discussing Hungary's political history or current events, as these topics can be sensitive and evoke strong feelings.\n\n10. **Footwear**: In private homes, it\u2019s customary to remove your shoes upon entering. Be prepared for a possible request to do so.\n\nBy being mindful of these cultural customs, you can show respect for Hungarian traditions and foster positive interactions during your visit.",
